Thank you.

203
00:22:30,060 --> 00:22:46,859
I have heard from some folks about our decision to not wait the lottery at all and got a couple of questions that I couldn't really answer about why we didn't at least

204
00:22:48,382 --> 00:23:01,009
ask kids to describe their interest or provide some sort of like meaningful input in some way versus like a blind lottery.

205
00:23:01,049 --> 00:23:15,997
So I guess my question is are there other schools who are doing something that is helping students be able to articulate their desire to be in various programs before the lottery is run.

206
00:23:16,017 --> 00:23:16,537
And I and

207
00:23:18,455 --> 00:23:22,932
Like, I think the fear is, right, I don't know what I'm going to do at the end.

208
00:23:23,757 --> 00:23:30,663
So I'm just going to put my name in for something because that's better than extended exploratory or study hall or whatever.

209
00:23:31,383 --> 00:23:40,151
And then I am actually taking a spot from somebody who really wanted to be in that shop, but I just happened to be the lucky one and that person's not.

210
00:23:40,571 --> 00:23:45,735
And then I drop out before the year is over or at the end of the year and don't continue.

211
00:23:45,855 --> 00:23:50,759
So I guess my question is, are there other models that we should be considering that would

212
00:23:51,660 --> 00:24:01,605
provide some sort of threshold of work or interest in some way that would be beneficial to explore in the future.

213
00:24:03,427 --> 00:24:06,849
Yeah, so the state offers some opportunities if you want to do a weighted lottery.

214
00:24:06,889 --> 00:24:12,732
Most of the schools I've talked to and a lot of the colleagues I have in the area did not do a weighted lottery, but you can.

215
00:24:12,972 --> 00:24:14,893
And it's looking at attendance the year before.

216
00:24:15,073 --> 00:24:18,355
They want to see that students haven't missed anything more than 27 days.

217
00:24:18,595 --> 00:24:24,198
So if you're somebody who didn't miss 27 days or more, you would get, you know, essentially another ball in the lottery.

218
00:24:24,779 --> 00:24:31,983
If you're somebody who hasn't had any 37H or 37H and a half in fractions with discipline, then you would get a second ball in the lottery.

219
00:24:32,789 --> 00:24:37,576
And then if you attend an open house or you come to in a community event you might get a third ball in the lottery.

220
00:24:38,377 --> 00:24:49,012
So when we talked about it as a district team we didn't feel like that selective criteria was necessarily going to hurt or help any students because most of our students don't miss 30 plus days of school so.

221
00:24:49,953 --> 00:24:57,357
This was really the Department of Education's way of saying, okay, we understand you might want to use some weights and how you do it, but we're going to prescribe how you do it.

222
00:24:57,817 --> 00:24:59,658
The other piece is like an interview.

223
00:25:00,418 --> 00:25:02,059
So, you know, this was year one.

224
00:25:02,079 --> 00:25:06,861
I am happy to bring it back to the team and bring people around the table and talk about what that may look like.

225
00:25:06,881 --> 00:25:10,783
And if the district decides they want to do a weighted lottery, then we can look at that too.

226
00:25:12,408 --> 00:25:21,536
Yeah, I guess I would say that those three weights don't seem like they would actually be meaningful for us here or for our problem.

227
00:25:21,556 --> 00:25:32,825
I mean, I understand what the state is trying to do when it comes to regional vocational schools and the admission, which is you're either in or you're not in at all.

228
00:25:33,626 --> 00:25:37,769
And that's a distinctly different challenge than we have.

229
00:25:37,850 --> 00:25:39,451
So those criteria don't

230
00:25:40,137 --> 00:25:43,381
really like compel me in any particular way.

231
00:25:43,401 --> 00:26:00,041
I am more interested in making sure that there's there's the seats for the students who need there to be seats in our district, which doesn't happen in quite the same way that it happens in most of these regional vocational schools.

232
00:26:00,461 --> 00:26:04,723
And frankly we weren't the reason why the state enacted this legislation in the first place.

233
00:26:04,783 --> 00:26:19,109
So my first preference would be the state says people like Medford don't have to participate in this process at all because our students are in Medford High School no matter whether they are in program a program B or no program.

234
00:26:19,209 --> 00:26:22,751
That is not the case in the regional vocational schools and there's huge demand.

235
00:26:22,831 --> 00:26:28,914
So I guess what I'm trying to do is figure out like are there other things that we could do

236
00:26:29,645 --> 00:26:47,028
that make sure that we are helping students take like understand what action they can take to express their preferences and desires other than just like feeling like it's really random whether you're going to get to do the thing that you wanted to do or not.

237
00:26:47,823 --> 00:26:49,485
No, I really appreciate you saying that.

238
00:26:49,745 --> 00:26:59,917
And what I will say is that this year, because we knew it was going to be a change, we spent a week that was focused on career connected activities where students went through a preliminary selection.

239
00:26:59,937 --> 00:27:05,664
I then packaged all the responses home, sent them home to families and said, hey, over the winter break.

240
00:27:06,505 --> 00:27:09,887
take a moment to talk about this with your son or daughter because this is an important decision.

241
00:27:10,547 --> 00:27:29,717
So I can tell you that this year we have really flooded people's email and talking points with like this is really important we want to make sure people get placed in their their areas and the good thing is when we look back and by the way there was probably about 20 percent of students that changed their responses from the preliminary to the final pick which was encouraging for me because it showed me that kids were thinking

242
00:27:31,358 --> 00:27:37,947
Also, for 90% of our students to be placed in their first choice, that was huge, or to be placed in one of their top two choices.

243
00:27:38,788 --> 00:27:47,739
So, you know, even though we do have, you know, a number of kids that didn't get electrical health assisting construction because they kind of chose, you know, within that group.

244
00:27:48,460 --> 00:27:53,722
There were so many kids that did get their choices, which was like, okay, so we're headed in the right direction.

245
00:27:54,162 --> 00:28:02,445
But what you're saying is very true, Jenny, but also I want to call out that the other option we could do that I've been very much against since the beginning, but I'm willing to talk it out if need be.

246
00:28:03,085 --> 00:28:07,487
If we did a lottery in eighth grade, which we could do, some districts have done that just like the regionals.

247
00:28:07,927 --> 00:28:13,849
What worries me is all the work we've done for the past 10, 11 years about being one school and kind of coming together.

248
00:28:14,270 --> 00:28:16,951
I'm afraid that people will be like, oh, are you applying to the VOC?

249
00:28:17,151 --> 00:28:18,471
Are you applying to Medford VOC?

250
00:28:18,551 --> 00:28:19,392
I'm applying to the VOC.

251
00:28:19,412 --> 00:28:32,397
And then if I take in 180 students in grade nine, because I know that's how many I can seat in grade 10, I feel like we could be going backwards and then trying to backfill because we know 20 to 30% of the kids end up deciding it's not for me.

252
00:28:33,217 --> 00:28:41,641
So I would hate to see us in a position this time in a freshman year looking to then pull kids in who didn't choose CTE Exploratory.

253
00:28:41,701 --> 00:28:45,443
So that's something that we can definitely discuss more.

254
00:28:45,503 --> 00:28:51,086
But my personal opinion was, especially for Medford, the eighth grade pick didn't feel right to me.

255
00:28:51,106 --> 00:28:53,548
It feels like it goes against everything we've been trying to do.

256
00:28:54,068 --> 00:28:56,809
Please don't discuss that more.

257
00:28:57,610 --> 00:28:57,830
Got it.

258
00:28:59,333 --> 00:29:04,482
Yeah, that's exactly the opposite of what I think we're trying to do here.

259
00:29:06,045 --> 00:29:12,356
When Lila was a freshman, all freshmen went through an exploratory program, and I think there's

260
00:29:13,002 --> 00:29:17,404
immense value in that, especially if you're talking about eighth graders making these kinds of choices.

261
00:29:17,924 --> 00:29:19,845
My preference would be that we go back to that model.

262
00:29:19,885 --> 00:29:27,347
But that aside, like, I'm not interested in, like, sealing somebody's fate at the, you know, whatever age it is that you're in eighth grade.

263
00:29:28,108 --> 00:29:31,289
Like, that seems like it's much too early, much, much too early.

264
00:29:31,309 --> 00:29:34,610
And I'm not interested in that at all.

265
00:29:35,050 --> 00:29:36,591
I'm just more interested in,

266
00:29:37,732 --> 00:29:50,530
How do we make sure that the kids who are in Medford High, who have gone through the rotation program, that you don't have to be one of the 10% of kids that don't land where you wanted to.

267
00:29:51,899 --> 00:29:58,622
If there's other shuffling that could like make way for those 10% of kids to find their home a little bit faster, I think it would be ideal.

268
00:29:58,662 --> 00:30:11,628
So I'm not sure what the answer is necessarily, but that's what I would want us to be focused on is like, how do we get even closer than 90% from a placement perspective?

269
00:30:12,188 --> 00:30:15,770
And as importantly, how do we have pathways out for kids that

270
00:30:16,890 --> 00:30:25,160
are not interested in continuing so that they don't make decisions to sort of stay in or delay that exit decision because I think that's not fun for them either.

271
00:30:25,180 --> 00:30:33,969
So, yeah, I think, you know, there's probably a lot more discussion to have around what those options might be.

272
00:30:36,011 --> 00:30:41,236
I do think it's, you know, it's easy to, like, pick three things on a form, right?

273
00:30:41,956 --> 00:30:48,141
It's another to express interest or, like, any sort of desire to be in a program.

274
00:30:48,241 --> 00:30:53,525
And I just wonder if there isn't a way for that to come through somehow in our process.

275
00:30:53,605 --> 00:30:55,587
But maybe there's not.

276
00:30:56,948 --> 00:31:00,330
No, we are, this is something I talk about every day.

277
00:31:00,390 --> 00:31:01,310
How can we make this better?

278
00:31:01,350 --> 00:31:05,633
I mean, obviously the ultimate answer is hire more teachers, build more space, right?

279
00:31:05,653 --> 00:31:06,994
Because we know what programs they want.

280
00:31:07,014 --> 00:31:25,724
And this is the case in a lot of schools, but the worst part of my job every year is program selection because we always know the programs that fill and it's not fun meeting with a student and telling them that they didn't get in for whatever reason, especially if their family's in the trade or it's a painful process, but we are working to make it better.

281
00:31:27,095 --> 00:31:27,415
Thank you.

282
00:31:29,816 --> 00:31:30,137
Thank you.

283
00:31:30,937 --> 00:31:32,778
We have a, Christine, come on up.

284
00:31:34,119 --> 00:31:38,821
If member Mastroboni or member Graham, if you could share your, oh, unless that works.

285
00:31:42,303 --> 00:31:54,229
If someone's like in the VOC already and they, let's say they didn't get their first choice or they changed their mind after that freshman year, are they, do they go through the same like

286
00:31:55,505 --> 00:31:58,886
lottery process again, or is there like a separate process for that?

287
00:31:59,746 --> 00:32:01,127
Because they're already doing that.

288
00:32:02,507 --> 00:32:04,948
So are you, are you saying, go ahead.

289
00:32:06,108 --> 00:32:07,749
Are you saying... Great question, go ahead, sorry.

290
00:32:08,189 --> 00:32:08,469
Oh, no.

291
00:32:08,769 --> 00:32:17,631
Are you saying if a student picks a program, gets a spot, let's say they get a spot in health assisting, and then they decide maybe this time of the year that they're not happy and they wanna change to another program?

292
00:32:18,492 --> 00:32:19,472
What the process is?

293
00:32:20,472 --> 00:32:22,993
Or if at the end of their freshman year, let's say they got their

294
00:32:23,767 --> 00:32:28,451
third choice or they didn't get one of their top choices and they really want to change to something else.

295
00:32:29,231 --> 00:32:29,832
Yeah.

296
00:32:30,693 --> 00:32:30,933
Yes.

297
00:32:31,093 --> 00:32:39,200
So we're already what's already happening is like today, for example, I had that I know of one definitely and probably another one in health assisting that has decided it's not for them.

298
00:32:39,500 --> 00:32:42,763
So now those students will move out and maybe they'll go to another program.

299
00:32:42,783 --> 00:32:46,426
In one case, one student wanted to go to biotech and there's no wait list right now for biotech.

300
00:32:46,466 --> 00:32:47,807
So that was a clean transfer.

301
00:32:48,347 --> 00:32:54,530
So we're going to make every opportunity, if somebody is going from health assisting to electrical, obviously there's a long wait for electrical.

302
00:32:54,570 --> 00:33:01,393
But what we do is we look at any, if they want a specific program and there's room available, we either add them to the program or we add them to the wait list.

303
00:33:01,913 --> 00:33:03,194
We don't do another lottery.

304
00:33:03,454 --> 00:33:05,414
We did lottery for first and second choice.

305
00:33:05,955 --> 00:33:14,318
And once we did that first round, now at this point in the year, if people decide they want to be added to a wait list, they just reach out to me and their counselor and we add them to the wait list.

306
00:33:14,338 --> 00:33:15,579
There's not an additional lottery.

307
00:33:18,510 --> 00:33:19,711
Okay, thank you.

308
00:33:20,151 --> 00:33:20,471
You're welcome.

309
00:33:20,611 --> 00:33:20,931
Thank you.

310
00:33:22,412 --> 00:33:23,592
Thank, thank you Mr. Fallon.

311
00:33:24,073 --> 00:33:24,393
Welcome.

312
00:33:25,013 --> 00:33:27,874
Thank you Principal Fallon and thank you Dr. Galussi for the presentation.

313
00:33:27,894 --> 00:33:29,355
Is there a motion on the floor?

314
00:33:29,375 --> 00:33:30,956
I think we need a vote.

315
00:33:31,716 --> 00:33:32,296
That's what I figured.

316
00:33:32,316 --> 00:33:34,897
Thank you.

317
00:33:34,917 --> 00:33:35,038
Yes.

318
00:33:36,458 --> 00:33:47,043
Yes, we do need a, a vote to update the policy with the Department of Education's suggested suggestions and edits so that we can get that vote.

319
00:33:51,102 --> 00:33:55,704
Motion to approve by Member Mastraboni, seconded by Member Lopate.

320
00:33:56,064 --> 00:33:56,844
All those in favor?

321
00:33:56,864 --> 00:33:56,924
Aye.

322
00:33:57,944 --> 00:33:58,785
All those opposed?

323
00:34:00,245 --> 00:34:00,965
Motion passes.

324
00:34:02,966 --> 00:34:07,087
Next up, we have our fiscal year 26-27 calendar review.

325
00:34:07,107 --> 00:34:10,248
So I'm going to turn it over to Dr. Suzanne Galluzzi, our superintendent.

326
00:34:12,609 --> 00:34:12,989
Thank you.

327
00:34:17,042 --> 00:34:17,462
Okay.

328
00:34:18,083 --> 00:34:19,143
Thank you, Mr. Pippicelli.

329
00:34:19,163 --> 00:34:21,204
You can advance to the next slide.

330
00:34:22,144 --> 00:34:37,091
So this evening I just want, I'm here in a collaborative problem solving kind of stance and effort here to frame a little bit of next year's calendar based on this year's calendar.

331
00:34:38,392 --> 00:34:49,187
Throughout the course of this year, I have received some feedback and information regarding school calendars, as would be typical from caregivers, from staff.

332
00:34:49,287 --> 00:34:54,874
And so three things have kind of, you know, risen in terms of like impact to the calendar.

333
00:34:55,895 --> 00:35:00,856
One is our placement of professional development days and where they are.

334
00:35:01,056 --> 00:35:18,960
Some caregivers have mentioned that this year we put them all on a Tuesday, and so for some people, depending on their work structure or just available care for their children during the day, there were some kind of queries around, do we always have to have them on Tuesday?

335
00:35:19,800 --> 00:35:26,543
The other one is just the acknowledgement of the impact that Good Friday had for a large part of our community.

336
00:35:27,624 --> 00:35:29,845
And that we have to take that into effect for next year.

337
00:35:30,625 --> 00:35:38,269
And then this year for the first time in a couple years, we did not have a mild winter and we needed four snow days.

338
00:35:38,850 --> 00:35:43,492
And so per the Department of Education, we have to build in five snow days.

339
00:35:44,032 --> 00:35:47,354
And so this year we used four out of those five.

340
00:35:48,963 --> 00:35:50,344
So next slide please.

341
00:35:50,424 --> 00:35:55,946
I just want to frame a little bit about what the calendar looks like for next school year.

342
00:35:55,966 --> 00:35:58,887
All right.

343
00:35:58,947 --> 00:36:02,289
So next school year Labor Day is very late.

344
00:36:03,009 --> 00:36:05,310
Labor Day is September 7th.

345
00:36:06,210 --> 00:36:10,652
Typically what we have done is we've gone back the week before Labor Day.

346
00:36:11,232 --> 00:36:16,774
But what that does next year is that teachers report on the 31st that Monday.

347
00:36:18,698 --> 00:36:24,340
which were already pretty much in September, and then students, their first day is Wednesday, September 2nd.

348
00:36:25,140 --> 00:36:31,442
So we've kind of lost really like a whole week in August because of where Labor Day fell.

349
00:36:33,582 --> 00:36:34,343
We also have

350
00:36:36,734 --> 00:36:43,716
currently the observance of Yom Kippur in the calendar, Christmas Eve and Eid al-Fitr in the calendar.

351
00:36:43,736 --> 00:36:50,998
And then our three professional development days after September 2nd are Tuesday, November 3rd.

352
00:36:51,418 --> 00:36:57,460
That date is pretty fixed because that is an election day and our schools are used as polling places.

353
00:36:58,160 --> 00:37:03,622
So we typically, we have always had that day off and really need to continue to have that day off.

354
00:37:04,482 --> 00:37:06,063
Tuesday, January 19th.

355
00:37:06,403 --> 00:37:11,366
Yes, it's a Tuesday, but it is the Tuesday that follows the Martin Luther King weekend.

356
00:37:12,006 --> 00:37:20,251
We felt like that was an intentional move for caregivers that gave them a little bit of an opportunity to have like a longer weekend.

357
00:37:21,412 --> 00:37:25,774
And then Tuesday, March 2nd, it is another Tuesday.

358
00:37:26,015 --> 00:37:27,215
It's just a random day.

359
00:37:27,255 --> 00:37:28,256
There really is no rhyme.

360
00:37:28,870 --> 00:37:30,191
or reason for that day.

361
00:37:31,312 --> 00:37:43,622
All of this with DESE's requirement for us to build in five snow days, health days, emergency days, brings us to June 30th.

362
00:37:44,743 --> 00:37:49,126
So we don't have wiggle room because school needs to commence by June 30th.

363
00:37:50,865 --> 00:37:56,111
So I'm here to just frame this for you.

364
00:37:56,131 --> 00:37:57,952
I do not want to vote.

365
00:37:58,593 --> 00:37:59,874
I'm not here with an answer.

366
00:38:00,675 --> 00:38:03,458
Mr. Pippicelli, if you could advance the last slide.

367
00:38:04,039 --> 00:38:05,841
I just want to talk a little bit about

368
00:38:07,448 --> 00:38:11,391
my next steps as the superintendent of schools.

369
00:38:12,111 --> 00:38:15,633
So I had a conversation with Mr. Guillen.

370
00:38:15,673 --> 00:38:19,196
We want to create a committee or have some discussions.

371
00:38:20,256 --> 00:38:26,800
He's the president of the teachers union so that we can work collaboratively on the constraints of the calendar for next year.

372
00:38:28,441 --> 00:38:42,688
I would like to elicit some community input on the school calendar, especially since I received some feedback about where professional development days land, so I think it would be important to elicit some community input.

373
00:38:43,308 --> 00:38:49,590
around where professional development days are scheduled and also holidays.

374
00:38:50,150 --> 00:39:00,412
And then we are internally further reviewing our protocols and structures for the use of religious holidays by staff members across the district and throughout the school year.

375
00:39:01,012 --> 00:39:06,514
And then all of this I would bring back to this body with a presentation

376
00:39:07,574 --> 00:39:22,140
for a proposal as to what would be the best way for us to update school year 26-27 calendar based on the feedback I get from the community and the work with the teachers union.

377
00:39:23,821 --> 00:39:25,582
So again, I'm not looking for problems to be solved.

378
00:39:26,542 --> 00:39:26,982
I just wanted to

379
00:39:31,480 --> 00:39:43,383
explain to you in a collaborative stance that this is the work that we're going to be engaging in, and I will report back once we have a proposal as to what is the best way to proceed.

380
00:39:44,923 --> 00:39:47,063
Just one question from the chair.

381
00:39:47,203 --> 00:39:47,443
Yes.

382
00:39:48,544 --> 00:39:51,144
And you'll be relooking at April?

383
00:39:51,424 --> 00:39:51,704
Yes.

384
00:39:52,265 --> 00:39:54,305
And potentially bringing school

385
00:39:55,229 --> 00:39:57,871
taken off on Good Friday just because of the staffing.

386
00:39:58,452 --> 00:39:58,612
Yes.

387
00:39:58,632 --> 00:39:58,932
Issues.

388
00:39:59,192 --> 00:39:59,413
Yes.

389
00:39:59,653 --> 00:40:04,997
So I think what we have to, we, that has to be an acknowledgment 100% based on our staff.

390
00:40:05,077 --> 00:40:11,583
I think the school committee policy represents our school and city community.

391
00:40:12,083 --> 00:40:15,206
It doesn't necessarily represent our staff.

392
00:40:16,447 --> 00:40:21,511
And so I think we have to absolutely account for that in next year's calendar.

393
00:40:22,012 --> 00:40:22,932
What that looks like.

394
00:40:23,953 --> 00:40:28,854
I'm not quite sure of, because we have to engage in those conversations with the union.

395
00:40:29,514 --> 00:40:31,515
But yes, that would be the purpose of it.

396
00:40:31,575 --> 00:40:38,636
And so right now, I can't just say we'll add Good Friday back to the calendar, because I don't have that wiggle room.

397
00:40:39,457 --> 00:40:43,178
So that may not be the problem for the 27-28 calendar, or for the 28-29 calendar.

398
00:40:43,198 --> 00:40:47,339
But for next year, for the 26-27 calendar, because Labor Day is so late, that is the problem.

399
00:40:55,021 --> 00:41:04,748
a trade or there has to be, we have to look at the existing calendar and really have some discussions collaboratively about what is the best way to proceed.

400
00:41:05,088 --> 00:41:05,869
So some give and take.

401
00:41:05,949 --> 00:41:06,129
Okay.

402
00:41:06,169 --> 00:41:06,349
Yes.

403
00:41:06,389 --> 00:41:07,009
That makes sense.

